#: ../../../development/contributing.md:3
#: ../../../development/contributing.md:102
msgid "How to Contribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:5
msgid ""
"Thank you for your interest in contributing to Pyodide! There are many ways "
"to contribute, and we appreciate all of them. Here are some guidelines & "
"pointers for diving into it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:9
msgid "Development Workflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:11
msgid "To contribute code, see the following steps,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:13
msgid ""
"Fork the Pyodide repository [https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide](https://"
"github.com/pyodide/pyodide) on Github."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:14
msgid ""
"If you are on Linux, you can skip this step. On Windows and MacOS you have a "
"choice. The first option is to manually install Docker:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:16
msgid ""
"on MacOS follow [these instructions](https://docs.docker.com/desktop/mac/"
"install/)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:17
msgid ""
"on Windows, [install WSL 2](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/"
"install), then Docker. Note that Windows filesystem access from WSL2 is very "
"slow and should be avoided when building Pyodide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:22
msgid ""
"The second option is to use a service that provides a Linux development "
"environment, such as"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:24
msgid "[Github Codespaces](https://github.com/features/codespaces)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:25
msgid "[gitpod.io](https://gitpod.io)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:26
msgid "or a remote Linux VM with SSH connection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:28
msgid "Clone your fork of Pyodide"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:29
msgid "git clone --recursive https://github.com/<your-username>/pyodide.git\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:32
msgid "and add the upstream remote,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:33
msgid "git remote add upstream https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide.git\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:36
msgid ""
"While the build will happen inside Docker you still need a development "
"environment with Python 3.14 and ideally Node.js. These can be installed for "
"instance with,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:39
msgid ""
"conda env create -f environment.yml\n"
"conda activate pyodide-env\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:43
msgid "or via your system package manager."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:44
msgid ""
"Install requirements (it's recommended to use a virtualenv or a conda env),"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:45
msgid "pip install -r requirements.txt\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:48
msgid "Enable [prek](https://prek.j178.dev/) for code style,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:50
msgid "prek install\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:54
msgid "This will run a set of linters for each commit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:56
msgid "Follow {ref}`building_from_source` instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:58
msgid "See {ref}`testing` documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:60
msgid "Code of Conduct"
msgstr "行為守則"

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:62
msgid ""
"Pyodide has adopted a {ref}`code-of-conduct` that we expect all contributors "
"and core members to adhere to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:65
msgid "Development"
msgstr "開發"

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:67
msgid ""
"Work on Pyodide happens on GitHub. Core members and contributors can make "
"Pull Requests to fix issues and add features, which all go through the same "
"review process. We’ll detail how you can start making PRs below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:71
msgid ""
"We’ll do our best to keep `main` in a non-breaking state, ideally with tests "
"always passing. The unfortunate reality of software development is sometimes "
"things break. As such, `main` cannot be expected to remain reliable at all "
"times. We recommend using the latest stable version of Pyodide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:76
msgid ""
"Pyodide follows [semantic versioning](http://semver.org/) - major versions "
"for breaking changes (x.0.0), minor versions for new features (0.x.0), and "
"patches for bug fixes (0.0.x)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:80
msgid ""
"We keep a file, {ref}`docs/project/changelog.md <changelog>`, outlining "
"changes to Pyodide in each release. We like to think of the audience for "
"changelogs as non-developers who primarily run the latest stable. So the "
"change log will primarily outline user-visible changes such as new features "
"and deprecations, and will exclude things that might otherwise be "
"inconsequential to the end user experience, such as infrastructure or "
"refactoring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:87
msgid "Bugs & Issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:89
msgid ""
"We use [Github Issues](https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide/issues) for "
"announcing and discussing bugs and features. Use [this link](https://github."
"com/pyodide/pyodide/issues/new) to report a bug or issue. We provide a "
"template to give you a guide for how to file optimally. If you have the "
"chance, please search the existing issues before reporting a bug. It's "
"possible that someone else has already reported your error. This doesn't "
"always work, and sometimes it's hard to know what to search for, so consider "
"this extra credit. We won't mind if you accidentally file a duplicate report."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:99
msgid ""
"Core contributors are monitoring new issues & comments all the time, and "
"will label & organize issues to align with development priorities."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:104
msgid ""
"Pull requests are the primary mechanism we use to change Pyodide. GitHub "
"itself has some [great documentation](https://help.github.com/articles/about-"
"pull-requests/) on using the Pull Request feature. We use the \"fork and "
"pull\" model [described here](https://help.github.com/articles/about-pull-"
"requests/), where contributors push changes to their personal fork and "
"create pull requests to bring those changes into the source repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:112
msgid "Please make pull requests against the `main` branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:114
msgid ""
"If you’re looking for a way to jump in and contribute, our list of [good "
"first issues](https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide/labels/"
"good%20first%20issue) is a great place to start."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:118
msgid ""
"If you’d like to fix a currently-filed issue, please take a look at the "
"comment thread on the issue to ensure no one is already working on it. If no "
"one has claimed the issue, make a comment stating you’d like to tackle it in "
"a PR. If someone has claimed the issue but has not worked on it in a few "
"weeks, make a comment asking if you can take over, and we’ll figure it out "
"from there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:124
msgid ""
"We use [pytest](https://pytest.org), driving [Selenium](https://www."
"seleniumhq.org) as our testing framework. Every PR will automatically run "
"through our tests, and our test framework will alert you on GitHub if your "
"PR doesn’t pass all of them. If your PR fails a test, try to figure out "
"whether or not you can update your code to make the test pass again, or ask "
"for help. As a policy we will not accept a PR that fails any of our tests, "
"and will likely ask you to add tests if your PR adds new functionality. "
"Writing tests can be scary, but they make open-source contributions easier "
"for everyone to assess. Take a moment and look through how we’ve written our "
"tests, and try to make your tests match. If you are having trouble, we can "
"help you get started on our test-writing journey."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:136
msgid ""
"All code submissions should pass `make lint`. Python is checked with `ruff` "
"(for linting and formatting) and `mypy`. JavaScript and TypeScript are "
"checked with `biome`. C is checked with `clang-format`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:140
msgid "Contributing to the “core” C Code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:142
msgid "See {ref}`contributing-core`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:144
msgid "Documentation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:146
msgid ""
"Documentation is a critical part of any open source project, and we are very "
"welcome to any documentation improvements. Pyodide has a documentation "
"written in Markdown in the `docs/` folder. We use the [MyST](https://myst-"
"parser.readthedocs.io/en/latest/using/syntax.html#targets-and-cross-"
"referencing) for parsing Markdown in sphinx. You may want to have a look at "
"the [MyST syntax guide](https://myst-parser.readthedocs.io/en/latest/using/"
"syntax.html#the-myst-syntax-guide) when contributing, in particular "
"regarding [cross-referencing sections](https://myst-parser.readthedocs.io/en/"
"latest/using/syntax.html#targets-and-cross-referencing)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:155
msgid "Building the docs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:157
msgid ""
"From the directory `docs`, first install the Python dependencies with `pip "
"install -r requirements-doc.txt`. You also need to install JsDoc, which is a "
"`node` dependency. Install it with `sudo npm install -g jsdoc`. Then to "
"build the docs run `make html`. The built documentation will be in the "
"subdirectory `docs/_build/html`. To view them, cd into `_build/html` and "
"start a file server, for instance `http-server`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:164
msgid "Migrating patches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:166
msgid ""
"It often happens that patches need to be migrated between different versions "
"of upstream packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:169
msgid "If patches fail to apply automatically, one solution can be to"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:171
msgid ""
"Checkout the initial version of the upstream package in a separate repo, and "
"create a branch from it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:173
msgid "Add existing patches with `git apply <path.path>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:174
msgid ""
"Checkout the new version of the upstream package and create a branch from it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:175
msgid "Cherry-pick patches to the new version,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:176
msgid "git cherry-pick <commit-hash>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:179
msgid "and resolve conflicts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:180
msgid "Re-export last `N` commits as patches e.g."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/contributing.md:181
msgid "git format-patch -<N> -N --no-stat HEAD -o <out_dir>\n"
msgstr ""

